  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.2.0 (24a9fb8 2022-07-02T00:03:35.337245982Z)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\nforge fmt\n\n### Operating System\n\nLinux\n\n### Describe the bug\n\n# Description\r\n\r\n`forge fmt` always takes input from stdin when both of these conditions are met:\r\n\r\n- there's content in stdin; and\r\n- a path is specified as `forge fmt /path/to/folder/or/file`\r\n\r\nThis is troublesome because GitHub Actions seems to always attach an empty stdin to scripts, and thus makes any use of `forge fmt --check /path/to/folder` fail.\r\n\r\nIMO stdin should only be used when the \"path\" is \"-\", as with many Linux commands.\r\n\r\n## Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nRun this in a well formatted project:\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n$ printf \"\" | forge fmt --check src\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Expected result\r\n\r\nThe command should succeed because \"-\" is not used and path is specified.\r\n\r\n## Actual result\r\n\r\nThe command fails:\r\n\r\n```log\r\nDiff in stdin:\r\n    1    |+\r\n```",
